a(n) = A000005(n) - A048105(n); number of nonzero terms in row n of table A225817. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jul 30 2013
a(n) = Sum_{d|n} lambda(d)*mu(d)), where lambda is A008836. - _Enrique Pérez Herrero_, Apr 27 2014
L.g.f.: -log(Product_{k>=1} (1 - mu(k)^2*x^k)^(1/k)) = Sum_{n>=1} a(n)*x^n/n. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jul 30 2018
a(n) = Sum_{d|n} A001615(d) * A023900(n/d). - _Torlach Rush_, Jan 20 2020

A034676.name: Sum of squares of unitary divisors of n.
formula: Dirichlet g.f.: zeta(s)*zeta(s-2)/zeta(2*s-2). - _R. J. Mathar_, Mar 04 2011
Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ 30 * Zeta(3) * n^3 / Pi^4. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jan 11 2019

A034677.name: Sum of cubes of unitary divisors of n.
formula: Dirichlet g.f.: zeta(s)*zeta(s-3)/zeta(2s-3). - _R. J. Mathar_, Mar 04 2011
If n = Product (p_j^k_j) then a(n) = Product (1 + p_j^(3*k_j)). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Nov 04 2018
Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ Pi^4 * n^4 / (360 * Zeta(5)). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Feb 01 2019

A034678.name: Sum of fourth powers of unitary divisors.
formula: Dirichlet g.f.: zeta(s)*zeta(s-4)/zeta(2*s-4). - _R. J. Mathar_, Mar 04 2011
If n = Product (p_j^k_j) then a(n) = Product (1 + p_j^(4*k_j)). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Nov 04 2018
Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ 189 * Zeta(5) * n^5 / Pi^6. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Feb 01 2019

A034679.name: Sum of fifth powers of unitary divisors.
formula: Dirichlet g.f.: zeta(s)*zeta(s-5)/zeta(2s-5). - _R. J. Mathar_, Apr 12 2011
If n = Product (p_j^k_j) then a(n) = Product (1 + p_j^(5*k_j)). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Nov 04 2018

A034680.name: Sum of sixth powers of unitary divisors.
formula: Dirichlet g.f.: zeta(s)*zeta(s-6)/zeta(2s-6). - _R. J. Mathar_, Apr 12 2011
If n = Product (p_j^k_j) then a(n) = Product (1 + p_j^(6*k_j)). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Nov 04 2018

A034681.name: Sum of seventh powers of unitary divisors.
formula: Dirichlet g.f.: zeta(s)*zeta(s-7)/zeta(2s-7). - _R. J. Mathar_, Apr 12 2011
If n = Product (p_j^k_j) then a(n) = Product (1 + p_j^(7*k_j)). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Nov 04 2018

A034682.name: Sum of eighth powers of unitary divisors.
formula: Dirichlet g.f.: zeta(s)*zeta(s-8)/zeta(2s-8). - _R. J. Mathar_, Apr 12 2011
If n = Product (p_j^k_j) then a(n) = Product (1 + p_j^(8*k_j)). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Nov 04 2018

A034683.name: Unitary abundant numbers: numbers k such that usigma(k) > 2*k.

A034684.name: If n = p_1^e_1 * ... * p_k^e_k, p_1 < ... < p_k primes, then a(n) = min { p_i^e_i }.

A034685.name: Least possible integer k/(product of digits k) for k with n digits.

A034686.name: a(n) = k, where k/(product of digits of k) is least possible integer for k with n digits.

A034687.name: Related to quintic factorial numbers A008548.
formula: E.g.f.: (1/5)*L_{-1/5}(25*x) - 1, where L_{k}(x) is the Laguerre polynomial. - _Stefano Spezia_, Aug 17 2019

A034688.name: Expansion of (1-25*x)^(-1/5), related to quintic factorial numbers A008548.
formula: E.g.f.: L_{-1/5}(25*x), where L_{k}(x) is the Laguerre polynomial. - _Stefano Spezia_, Aug 17 2019
D-finite with recurrence: n*a(n) +5*(-5*n+4)*a(n-1)=0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Jan 17 2020

A034689.name: a(n) = n-th sextic factorial number divided by 2.
formula: D-finite with recurrence: a(n) +2*(-3*n+2)*a(n-1)=0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Feb 24 2020

A034690.name: Sum of digits of all the divisors of n.

A034691.name: Euler transform of powers of 2 [1,2,4,8,16,...].
formula: Recurrence: a(n) = (1/n) * Sum_{m=1..n} a(n-m)*c(m) where c(m) = A083413(m).

A034692.name: a(n+1) = smallest number that is not the sum of a(n) or fewer terms of a(1),...,a(n).

A034693.name: Smallest k such that k*n+1 is prime.
formula: It seems that Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) is asymptotic to (zeta(2)-1)*n*log(n) where zeta(2)-1 = Pi^2/6-1 = 0.6449... . - _Benoit Cloitre_, Aug 11 2002

A034694.name: Smallest prime == 1 (mod n).
formula: a(n) = min{m: m = k*n + 1 with k > 0 and A010051(m) = 1}. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Dec 17 2013

A034695.name: Tau_6 (the 6th Piltz divisor function), the number of ordered 6-factorizations of n; Dirichlet convolution of number-of-divisors function (A000005) with A007426.
formula: Multiplicative with a(p^e) = binomial(e+5, e). - _Mitch Harris_, Jun 27 2005
The Piltz divisor functions hold for tau_j(*)tau_k = tau_{j+k}, where (*) means Dirichlet convolution.
G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} tau_5(k)*x^k/(1 - x^k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Oct 30 2018

A034696.name: Dirichlet convolution of primes (A000040) with themselves.

A034697.name: a(1)=1, a(n)= 1 + Sum a(p), p prime, p | n-1.

A034698.name: a(n) is the smallest prime such that a(1), ..., a(n-1) are squares mod a(n).

A034699.name: Largest prime power factor of n.
formula: If n = p_1^e_1 *...* p_k^e_k, p_1 < ... < p_k primes, then a(n) = Max_i p_i^e_i.
a(n) = a(m) iff m = d*a(n), where d is a divisor of A038610(a(n)). - _I. V. Serov_, June 19 2019

A034700.name: a(n) = smallest prime == 1 (mod 4) such that a(n) is a square mod a(i), all i<n.

A034701.name: a(n) is the smallest number not of the form a(i) (1<=i<=n-1) or a(i)+a(n-1) (1<=i<=n-2).

A034702.name: a(n+1) is the smallest number not of the form a(i), a(i) + a(n-1), or |a(i) - a(n-1)|.

A034703.name: Numbers of the form binomial(a+b+c, a) + binomial(a+b+c, b) + binomial(a+b+c, c), with a,b,c >= 1.

A034704.name: Largest number that can be made using only the digits of n, exponentiation and concatenation.

A034705.name: Numbers that are sums of consecutive squares.

A034706.name: Numbers which are sums of consecutive triangular numbers.

A034707.name: Numbers that are sums (of a nonempty sequence) of consecutive primes.

A034708.name: Numbers for which the sum of reciprocals of digits is an integer.

A034709.name: Numbers divisible by their last digit.

A034710.name: Positive numbers for which the sum of digits equals the product of digits.

A034711.name: Largest number whose base n representation does not repeat a pair of consecutive digits.

A034712.name: Largest number using only digits <= n that does not repeat a pair of consecutive digits.

A034713.name: Dirichlet convolution of powers of 2 (2,4,8,...) with themselves.

A034714.name: Dirichlet convolution of squares with themselves.
formula: Equals n^2*tau(n), where tau(n) = A000005(n) = number of divisors of n. - _Jon Perry_, Aug 28 2005
Row sums of triangle A134576. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Nov 02 2007
G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} k^2*x^k*(1 + x^k)/(1 - x^k)^3. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Oct 24 2018

G.f.: Sum_{n >= 1} q^(n^2)*( n^4*q^(3*n) - n^2*(n^2 + 4*n - 2)*q^(2*n) - n^2*(n^2 - 4*n - 2)*q^n + n^4 )/(1 - q^n)^3 - apply the operator q*d/dq twice to equation 5 in Arndt and set x = 1. - _Peter Bala_, Jan 21 2021

A034715.name: Dirichlet convolution of triangular numbers with themselves.
formula: Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ n^3*(log(n)/12 + (6*gamma - 1 + Pi^2)/36), where gamma is the Euler-Mascheroni constant A001620. (End)

A034716.name: Dirichlet convolution of factorials with themselves.

A034717.name: Dirichlet convolution of Catalan numbers (1,2,5,14...) with themselves.

A034718.name: Dirichlet convolution of b_n=n with b_n with b_n.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k*l*m = n} k*l*m, for positive integers k, l, m. This equals one sixth of the same sum over all integers. - _Ralf Stephan_, May 06 2005
Multiplicative with a(p^e) = p^e * binomial(e+2, 2). - _Mitch Harris_, Jun 27 2005
a(n) = n*A007425(n). Dirichlet convolution of A000027 by A038040. - _R. J. Mathar_, Mar 30 2011

Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ (2*log(n)^2 + (12*gamma - 2)*log(n) + 12*gamma^2 - 6*gamma - 12*sg1 + 1) * n^2 / 8, where gamma is the Euler-Mascheroni constant A001620 and sg1 is the first Stieltjes constant (see A082633). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Sep 11 2019
G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} k*tau(k)*x^k / (1 - x^k)^2, where tau = A000005. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Sep 22 2020

A034719.name: Dirichlet convolution of powers of 3 (3,9,27,...) with themselves.

A034720.name: Number of different words that can be formed from an n X n grid of letters, reading horizontally, vertically or diagonally.

A034721.name: a(n) = (10*n^3 - 9*n^2 + 2*n)/3 + 1.
formula: a(n) = A034720(n) + 1 for n > 0, where +1 counts the empty string.

A034723.name: a(n) = n-th sextic factorial number divided by 3.
formula: D-finite with recurrence: a(n) +3*(-2*n+1)*a(n-1)=0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Feb 24 2020

A034724.name: a(n) = n-th sextic factorial number divided by 4.
formula: D-finite with recurrence: a(n) +2*(-3*n+1)*a(n-1)=0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Jan 28 2020

A034726.name: Smallest integral value of m/(sum of digits of m) for any n-digit number m.

A034727.name: a(n) = that n-digit number m which gives minimal integral value of m/(sum of digits of m); in case of a tie pick the smallest.

A034729.name: a(n) = Sum_{ k, k|n } 2^(k-1).
formula: G.f.: Sum_{n>=1} 2^(n-1) * x^n / (1 - x^n). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Aug 21 2014
G.f.: Sum_{n>=1} x^n * Sum_{d|n} 1/(1 - x^d)^(n/d). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Aug 21 2014
a(n) = Sum_{k in row n of A215366} A008480(k) * A000005(A289508(k)). - _Gus Wiseman_, Sep 16 2018
a(n) = Sum_{c is a composition of n} A000005(gcd(c)). - _Gus Wiseman_, Sep 16 2018

A034730.name: Dirichlet convolution of b_n=1 with c_n=3^(n-1).

A034731.name: Dirichlet convolution of b_n=1 with Catalan numbers.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{d divides n} C(d-1) where C() are the Catalan numbers (A000108).
L.g.f.: -log(Product_{k>=1} (1 - x^k)^(binomial(2*k-2,k-1)/k^2)) = Sum_{n>=1} a(n)*x^n/n. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, May 23 2018
G.f.: Sum_{n>=1} (1 - sqrt(1 - 4*x^n))/2. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Jan 12 2021
G.f.: Sum_{n>=1} A000108(n-1) * x^n/(1 - x^n) where A000108(n) = binomial(2*n,n)/(n+1). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Jan 12 2021

A034732.name: Dirichlet convolution of b_n=1 with Bell numbers.

A034733.name: Dirichlet convolution of b_n=2^(n-1) with itself.

A034734.name: Dirichlet convolution of b_n=2^(n-1) with Fibonacci numbers.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} 2^(k-1) * x^k/(1 - x^k - x^(2*k)). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jul 24 2019

A034735.name: Dirichlet convolution of b_n=2^(n-1) with c_n=3^(n-1).

A034736.name: Dirichlet convolution of b_n=2^(n-1) with Primes (with 1).

A034737.name: Dirichlet convolution of b_n=2^(n-1) with sigma(n).

A034738.name: Dirichlet convolution of b_n = 2^(n-1) with phi(n).

A034739.name: Dirichlet convolution of b_n=2^(n-1) with Catalan numbers.

A034740.name: Dirichlet convolution of b_n=2^(n-1) with Bell numbers.

A034742.name: Dirichlet convolution of Moebius function mu(n) (A008683) with Catalan numbers (A000108).
formula: G.f. A(x) satisfies: Sum_{n>=1} A((x-x^2)^n) = x. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Jan 04 2015
a(n) = Sum_{d|n} Moebius(n/d) * binomial(2*(d-1), d-1)/d. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Jan 04 2015

A034744.name: Dirichlet convolution of Fibonacci numbers with themselves.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} Fibonacci(k) * x^k/(1 - x^k - x^(2*k)). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jul 24 2019

A034745.name: Dirichlet convolution of Fibonacci numbers with 3^(n-1).
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} 3^(k-1) * x^k/(1 - x^k - x^(2*k)). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jul 24 2019

A034746.name: Dirichlet convolution of Fibonacci numbers with Primes (with 1).

A034747.name: Dirichlet convolution of Fibonacci numbers with sigma(n).
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} sigma(k) * x^k/(1 - x^k - x^(2*k)). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jul 23 2019

A034748.name: Dirichlet convolution of Fibonacci numbers with phi(n).
formula: From definition a(n) = Sum_{d|n} F(d)*phi(n/d); also a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} gcd(F(k), F(k+n)) where F(k) denotes the k-th Fibonacci number. - _Benoit Cloitre_, May 25 2003
G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} phi(k) * x^k/(1 - x^k - x^(2*k)). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jul 23 2019
a(n) ~ phi^n / sqrt(5), where phi = A001622 = (1+sqrt(5))/2 is the golden ratio. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jul 23 2019

A034749.name: Dirichlet convolution of Fibonacci numbers with Catalan numbers.

A034750.name: Dirichlet convolution of Fibonacci numbers with Bell numbers.

A034754.name: Dirichlet convolution of 3^(n-1) with phi(n).
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} phi(k) * x^k / (1 - 3*x^k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Feb 14 2020
a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} 3^(gcd(k, n) - 1) = A054610(n)/3. - _Seiichi Manyama_, Apr 17 2021

A034755.name: Dirichlet convolution of 3^(n-1) with Catalan numbers.

A034756.name: Dirichlet convolution of 3^(n-1) with Bell numbers.

A034757.name: a(1)=1, a(n) = smallest odd number such that all sums of pairs of (not necessarily distinct) terms in the sequence are distinct.

A034758.name: Dirichlet convolution of primes (with 1) with Bell numbers.

A034759.name: Dirichlet convolution of primes (with 1) with themselves.

A034760.name: Dirichlet convolution of primes (with 1) with phi(n).

A034761.name: Dirichlet convolution of sigma(n) with itself.
formula: Multiplicative with a(2^e) = (n-1) 2^(n+2) + n + 5, a(p^e) = ((1+e)p^(e+3) - (3+e)(p^(e+2)-p-1) + 2)/2, p > 2. - _Mitch Harris_, Jun 27 2005
Equals A134577 * A000005. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Nov 02 2007
Also the Dirichlet convolution A000005 by A038040. - _R. J. Mathar_, Apr 01 2011

Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ Pi^2 * n^2 * (2*Pi^2 * log(n) + (4*gamma - 1)*Pi^2 + 24*Zeta'(2)) / 144, where gamma is the Euler-Mascheroni constant A001620 and Zeta'(2) = A073002. Equivalently, Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ Pi^4 * n^2 * (2*log(n) - 1 + 8*gamma - 48*log(A) + 4*log(2*Pi)) / 144, where A is the Glaisher-Kinkelin constant A074962. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jan 28 2019

A034762.name: Dirichlet convolution of primes (with 1) with sigma(n).

A034763.name: Dirichlet convolution of primes (with 1) with Catalan numbers.

A034764.name: Dirichlet convolution of sigma(n) with Catalan numbers.

A034765.name: Dirichlet convolution of sigma(n) with Bell numbers.

A034766.name: Dirichlet convolution of phi(n) with Catalan numbers.

A034767.name: Dirichlet convolution of phi(n) with Bell numbers.

A034768.name: Dirichlet convolution of Catalan numbers with themselves.

A034769.name: Dirichlet convolution of Catalan numbers with Bell numbers.

A034770.name: Dirichlet convolution of Bell numbers with themselves.

A034771.name: Dirichlet convolution of d(n) (# of divisors) with b_n=2^(n-1).

A034772.name: Dirichlet convolution of d(n) (number of divisors) with Fibonacci numbers.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} d(k) * x^k/(1 - x^k - x^(2*k)). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jul 23 2019

A034773.name: Dirichlet convolution of d(n) (number of divisors of n) with primes (with 1).

A034774.name: Dirichlet convolution of d(n) (# of divisors) with Catalan numbers.

A034775.name: Dirichlet convolution of d(n) (# of divisors) with Bell numbers.

A034776.name: Gozinta numbers: possible number of gozinta chains for some positive integer.

A034777.name: Dirichlet convolution of [ 1,1,1,... ] with Ramanujan numbers (A000594).

A034778.name: Dirichlet convolution of Ramanujan numbers (A000594) with themselves.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{d|n} tau(d)tau(n/d) where tau(n) = A000594(n) is Ramanujan's tau function.

A034781.name: Triangle of number of rooted trees with n >= 2 nodes and height h >= 1.

A034782.name: Numbers n such that A034693(n) = 3: 3n + 1 is prime, but neither n + 1 nor 2n + 1.

A034786.name: Number of linearly ordered Girard monoids of size n; number of t-norms on an n-chain inducing an involutive residual negator.

A034787.name: a(n) = n-th sextic factorial number divided by 5.
formula: D-finite with recurrence: a(n) +(-6*n+1)*a(n-1)=0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Feb 24 2020

A034788.name: a(n) = n-th sextic factorial number divided by 6.
formula: D-finite with recurrence: a(n) -6*n*a(n-1)=0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Feb 24 2020

A034789.name: Related to sextic factorial numbers A008542.
formula: D-finite with recurrence: n*a(n) +6*(-6*n+5)*a(n-1)=0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Jan 28 2020

A034791.name: a(n) is square mod a(i), i < n.

A034792.name: Lexicographically earliest sequence of pairwise coprime triangular numbers.

A034793.name: a(1)=1; thereafter a(n+1) is the least k > a(n) such that k is a square mod a(i) for all  i<= n.
formula: Apparently includes all positive squares along with 2, 3 and 13.

A034794.name: a(n) is the least prime p > a(n-1) such that a(n-1) is a quadratic residue mod p.

A034795.name: a(n-1) is a square mod a(n) and prime.

A034796.name: a(1)=1, a(n-1) is a square mod a(n), and a(n) > a(n-1).

A034798.name: Value of n considered as a game.
formula: a(n) = smallest number not equal to a(i) for some i representing a 1-bit in the binary expansion of n (least significant bit is 0th bit)

A034799.name: Triangle of number of labeled trees by number of nodes and number of labels.
formula: E.g.f.: r(x,y) - (1/2)*r(x,y)^2 + (1/2)*r(x^2) where r(x,y) is the e.g.f. for A008295 and r(x) is the o.g.f. for A000081. - _Sean A. Irvine_, Sep 04 2020

A034800.name: Triangle of number of node labeled trees by number of nodes and number of labels.

A034801.name: Triangle of Fibonomial coefficients (k=2).
formula: Fibonomial coefficients formed from sequence F_3k [ 2, 8, 34, ... ].
T(n, k) = Product_{j=0..k-1} Fibonacci(2*(n-j)) / Product_{j=1..k} Fibonacci(2*j).

A034802.name: Triangle of Fibonomial coefficients (k=3).
formula: Fibonomial coefficients formed from sequence F_4k [ 3 21 144 987 ... ].

A034803.name: Consider the sequence of 4-tuples {0,a,b,c} (c>=a+b; a,b,c>0)) which have the smallest integer 'c' required to reach {k,k,k,k} in n steps under map {r,s,t,u}->{|r-s|,|s-t|,|t-u|,|u-r|}. This sequence gives the second term 'a' of these quadruples.
formula: a(n)= Trib(2*q-3)+Trib(2*q-1) if r=0; Trib(2*q-2)+Trib(2*q-1) if r=1; Trib(2*q) if r=2 where q=[(n-1)/3], r=n-1 (mod 3) and Trib is the tribonacci sequence (A000073) with Trib(-3)=0, Trib(-2)=-1, Trib(-1)=1. G.f.: (x^8-2*x^7+3*x^6-x^5+2*x^3-1)/(x^9+x^6+3*x^3-1). Recurrence: a(n)=3*a(n-3)+a(n-6)+a(n-9), n >= 10.

A034804.name: Consider the sequence of 4-tuples {0,a,b,c} (c>=a+b; a,b,c>0)) which have the smallest integer 'c' required to reach {k,k,k,k} in n steps under map {r,s,t,u}->{|r-s|,|s-t|,|t-u|,|u-r|}. This sequence gives the third term 'b' of these quadruples.
formula: a(n)= 2*Trib(2*q) if r=0; Trib(2*q-1)+Trib(2*q+1) if r=1; Trib(2*q)+Trib(2*q+1) if r=2 where q=[(n-1)/3], r=n-1 (mod 3) and Trib denotes the tribonacci sequence (A000073) with Trib(-1)=1. G.f.: (-x^7+2*x^6-2*x^5+2*x^4-2*x^3-x)/(x^9+x^6+3*x^3-1). Recurrence: a(n)=3*a(n-3)+a(n-6)+a(n-9), n >= 10.

A034806.name: Number of distinct sets of 2 numbers > 1 such that their product is between n^2 and (n+1)^2.

A034807.name: Triangle T(n,k) of coefficients of Lucas (or Cardan) polynomials.
formula: Lucas polynomial coefficients: 1, -n, [n(n-3)]/2!, - [n(n-4)(n-5)]/3!, [n(n-5)(n-6)(n-7)]/4!, - [n(n-6)(n-7)(n-8)(n-9)]/5!... - _Herb Conn_ and _Gary W. Adamson_, May 28 2003

T(n, k) = T(n-1, k) + T(n-2, k-1), n>1. T(n, 0) = 1, n>0. T(n, k) = binomial(n-k, k) + binomial(n-k-1, k-1) = n*binomial(n-k-1, k-1)/k, 0 <= 2*k <= n except T(0, 0) = 2. - _Michael Somos_, Apr 02 1999
T(n,k) = (n*(n-1-k)!)/(k!*(n-2*k)!), n>0, k>=0. - Alexander Elkins (alexander_elkins(AT)hotmail.com), Jun 09 2007

A034808.name: Concatenation of 'prevprime(n) and n' is a prime.

A034809.name: Numbers k such that the concatenation of k and previous_prime(k) is a prime.

A034810.name: Concatenation of 'prevprime(n) and n and nextprime(n)' is a prime.

A034811.name: Concatenation of 'nextprime(n) and n and prevprime(n)' is a prime.

A034812.name: Concatenation of 'prevprime(n) and n and prevprime(n)' is a prime.

A034813.name: Concatenations C1 and C2 are both prime (see the comment lines).

A034814.name: Concatenations C1 and C2 are both prime (see the comment lines).

A034815.name: Concatenations C1 and C2 are both prime (see the comment lines).

A034816.name: Concatenations C1 and C2 are both prime (see the comment lines).

A034817.name: Concatenations C1 and C2 and C3 are all prime (see the comment lines).

A034818.name: Concatenations C1 and C2 and C3 are all prime (see the comment lines).

A034819.name: Concatenations C1 and C2 and C3 and C4 are all prime (see the comment lines).

A034820.name: Concatenations C1 and C2 and C3 and C4 are all prime (see the comment lines).

A034821.name: Concatenations C1 and C2 are both prime (see the comment lines).

A034822.name: Numbers n such that there are no palindromic squares of length n.

A034823.name: Number of n-node rooted trees of height at most 6.
formula: Take Euler transform of A001385 and shift right. (Christian G. Bower).

A034824.name: Number of n-node rooted trees of height at most 7.
formula: Take Euler transform of A034823 and shift right. (_Christian G. Bower_).

A034836.name: Number of ways to write n as n = x*y*z with 1 <= x <= y <= z.
formula: Given a number n, let s(1),...,s(m) be the signature list of n, and a(n) the resulting number in the sequence.

Then np = Product_{k=1..m} binomial(2+s(k),2) is the total number of products solely based on the combination of exponents. The multiplicity of powers is not taken into account (e.g., all combinations of 1,2,4 (6 times) but (2,2,2) only once). See next formulas to compute corrections for 3rd and 2nd powers.
Let ntp = Product_{k=1..m} (floor((s(k) - s(k) mod(3))/s(k))) if the number is a 3rd power or not resulting in 1 or 0.
Let nsq = Product_{k=1..m} (floor(s(k)/2) + 1) is the number of squares.
Example: n = 1728; s = [3,6]; np = 10*28 = 280; nsq = 2*4 = 8; ntp = 1 so a(1728)=51 (as in the b-file).
a(n) >= A226378(n) for all n >= 1. - _Antti Karttunen_, Aug 30 2017

a(n, k) = a(n-1, k-1) + a(n-1, k) - C(n/2-1, (k-1)/2), where the last term is present only if n even, k odd (see Sloane link).

formula: a(n) = A090802(2n-1, n). - _Ross La Haye_, Oct 18 2005

The sequence b(n) := a(n)* Sum {k = 0..n-1} (-1)^k/( 2^k*(2*k + 1)*binomial(2*k,k) ) beginning [1, 11, 222, 6210, 223584, ...] satisfies the same recurrence. This leads to the finite continued fraction expansion b(n)/a(n) = 1/(1 + 1/(11 + 24/(18 + 60/(25 + ... + 4*(n - 1)*(2*n - 3)/(7*n - 3) )))) for n >= 3.

Letting n tend to infinity gives the continued fraction expansion Sum {k = 0..inf} (-1)^k/( 2^k*(2*k + 1)*binomial(2*k,k) ) = 4/3*log(2) = 1/(1 + 1/(11 + 24/(18 + 60/(25 + ... + 4*(n - 1)*(2*n - 3)/((7*n - 3) + ... ))))). (End)
This sequence satisfies several other second order recurrence equations leading to some continued fraction expansions.

This recurrence is also satisfied by the (integer) sequence c(n) := a(n)*Sum {k = 0..n} 1/( 2^k*(2*k + 1)*binomial(2*k,k) ). From this we can obtain the continued fraction expansion Sum {k >= 0} 1/( 2^k*(2*k + 1)*binomial(2*k,k) ) = 8/sqrt(7)*arctan(sqrt(7)/7) = 8/sqrt(7)*A195699 = 1 + 1/(12 - 24/(22 - 60/(31 - ... - 4*n*(2*n - 1)/((9*n + 4) - ... )))).

This recurrence is also satisfied by the (integer) sequence d(n) := a(n)*Sum {k = 0..n} 1/( (2*k + 1)*2^k ). From this we can obtain the continued fraction expansion Sum {k >= 0} 1/( (2*k + 1)*2^k ) = 1/sqrt(2)*log(3 + 2*sqrt(2)) = 1 + 2/(12 - 8*3^2/(26 - 8*5^2/(38 - ... - 8*(2*n - 1)^2/((12*n + 2) - ... )))). Cf. A002391.

This recurrence is also satisfied by the (integer) sequence e(n) := a(n)*Sum {k = 0..n} (-1)^k/( (2*k + 1)*2^k ). From this we can obtain the continued fraction expansion Sum {k >= 0} (-1)^k/( (2*k + 1)*2^k ) = 1/sqrt(2)*arctan(sqrt(2)/2) = 1 - 2/(12 + 8*3^2/(14 + 8*5^2/(18 + ... + 8*(2*n - 1)^2/((4*n + 6) + ... )))). Cf. A073000. (End)

The closed form a(n) = (2n-1)!! (2n+1)^n can be obtained from the generating function. - _Noam D. Elkies_, Dec 16 2002
E.g.f. A(x) = series reversion of x*exp(-1/2*x^2) = sum {n >= 0} a(n)*x^(2*n+1)/(2*n+1)! = x + 3*x^3/3! + 75*x^5/5! + .... The Lagrange inversion formula gives a(n) = (2*n+1)^n*(2*n)!/(2^n*n!).
A(x)^2 = T(x^2), where T denotes the tree function T(x) := sum {n >= 1} n^(n-1)*x^n/n!. A(x)^r = sum {n >= 0} r*(2*n+r)^(n-1)*x^(2*n+r)/(2^n*n!).
